{"title_page": "Jon Batiste", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician and bandleader}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{about|the American musician|the American military officer and consultant|John Batiste}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jon Batiste\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Jon Batiste 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Batiste in 2018\n| birth_name       = Jonathan Michael Batiste<ref name=fdr1>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', January 7, 2020</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1986|11|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Metairie, Louisiana]], U.S.<ref name=fdr1/>\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*Jazz\n*blues\n*pop\n*rock\n*soul\n*R&B \n*funk\n*hip hop\n*classical}}\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n*Piano\n*voice\n*melodica\n*bass\n*organ\n*drums}}\n| years_active     = 1998\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]]\n| website          = {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Michael Batiste''' (born November 11, 1986)<ref name=\"Rose28Aug\">{{cite news | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/next-gen-fall-tv-10-817493 | title=Next Gen Fall TV: 10 Stars Poised for Breakouts | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=August 28, 2015 | accessdate=December 2, 2015 | first1=Lacey | last2=O'Connell | first2=Michael | last1=Rose | last3=Sandberg | first3=Bryn Elise | last4=Stanhope | first4=Kate | last5=Goldberg | first5=Lesley}}</ref> is an American musician, bandleader, and television personality.<ref>[http://observer.com/2015/07/stephen-colberts-new-bandleader-could-change-late-night-tv/ \"Stephen Colbert's New Bandleader Could Change Late Night TV\"] by Amanda Wicks, ''[[The New York Observer]]'', July 24, 2015</ref> He has recorded and performed with artists in various genres of music ([[Stevie Wonder]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Lenny Kravitz]], [[Ed Sheeran]], and [[Mavis Staples]]), released his own recordings, and performed in more than 40 countries. Batiste regularly tours with his band [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]],<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/18/arts/music/national-jazz-museum-in-harlem-plans-expansion.html | work=The New York Times | first=Robin | last=Pogrebin | title=National Jazz Museum in Harlem Plans Expansion | date=2012-06-17}}</ref> and appears with them nightly as bandleader and musical director on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]''.<ref name=\"Serico\">{{cite web |last1=Serico |first1=Chris |title='I like this guy': Stephen Colbert chooses Jon Batiste as 'Late Show' bandleader |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/stephen-colbert-names-jon-batiste-new-late-show-bandleader-t24636 |website=Today |accessdate=25 July 2018 |date=4 June 2015}}</ref> Batiste also serves as the Music Director of [[The Atlantic]] and the Creative Director of the [[National Jazz Museum in Harlem]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nJon Batiste was born in [[Metairie, Louisiana]], into a long line of musicians, including [[Lionel Batiste]] and [[Harold Battiste]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/jon-batiste|title=Jon Batiste|last1=Ehrlich|first1=Dimitri|date=November 11, 2013|website=[[Interview Magazine]]}}</ref> At the age of 8, he played percussion and drums with his family's band, the Batiste Brothers Band. At the age of 11, he switched to piano at his mother's suggestion. Jon developed his piano skills by taking classical music lessons and transcribing songs from video games such as ''[[Street Fighter Alpha]]'', ''[[Final Fantasy VII]]'' and ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weingarten |first1=Christopher |title=Meet Jon Batiste, Colbert's Crowd-Thrilling Bandleader|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/meet-jon-batiste-stephen-colberts-crowd-thrilling-rebel-bandleader-20150805|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt 17, Batiste released ''Times in New Orleans''. He attended [[St. Augustine High School (New Orleans)|St. Augustine High School]] and [[New Orleans Center for Creative Arts]] with [[Trombone Shorty]] in New Orleans and graduated in 2004. He then went on to receive a bachelor's and master's degree from the [[Juilliard School]]. While at Juilliard, he released his second album, ''Live in New York: At the Rubin Museum of Art.'' By the end of 2006, Batiste had been a featured performer in South Africa, London, Lisbon, Spain, Paris and the United States.<ref name=\"Salisbury University\">{{cite web | url=http://www.salisbury.edu/news/article.html?id=5069 | title=Award-Winning Jazz Artist Batiste Performs at SU Monday, September 24 | publisher=Salisbury University | date=12 September 2012 | accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources|section|date=January 2020}}\nIn 2007, Batiste made his debut at the [[Concertgebouw]] in Amsterdam at the age of 20, producing and performing his own show. He conducted music clinics, classes and workshops throughout the Netherlands in inner-city schools and underprivileged neighborhoods. He was invited to [[Carnegie Hall]] to produce and perform in his own show with six young musicians from the Netherlands. The performance concluded with a finale he composed for choir, jazz combo and orchestral instruments. In the following years, Batiste released a number of music projects including ''Social Music'' (2013), which spent over a month at the top of the Billboard and iTunes jazz charts; ''The Late Show EP'' (2016) with [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]]; and a holiday album ''Christmas with Jon Batiste'' (2016). In 2017, he released the singles \"Ohio\" with [[Leon Bridges]] and [[Gary Clark Jr.]] as well as \"Battle Hymn of the Republic\" for [[The Atlantic]]. Batiste's cover of \"St. James Infirmary Blues\" was nominated for a Grammy in 2019, in the category of Best American Roots Performance. Batiste\u2019s debut solo album ''Hollywood Africans'' was released by Verve Records in September 2018. \"Don't Stop\" served as the lead single. Leading up to the album release, he completed a Summer Festival tour across the U.S. with [[The Dap-Kings]].\n\nBatiste's notable career performances include a tribute to Chuck Berry and Fats Domino during the 60th annual Grammy Awards (performing alongside [[Gary Clark Jr.]]); the Kennedy Center Honors' tribute to Carmen De Lavallade; the Concert for Peace and Justice in Montgomery, Alabama; the National Anthem at the 2017 NBA All Star Game; and Opening Night of the 2017 US Open. He has curated the Global Citizen Advocacy Concert with Tom Morello and the Louis Armstrong Wonderful World Festival in Queens, N.Y.\n\n==Stay Human==\n\nIn 2005, Batiste began performing regularly in New York with his Juilliard peers, bassist Phil Kuehn and drummer [[Joe Saylor]]. He later added [[Eddie Barbash]] on alto saxophone and Ibanda Ruhumbika on tuba.<ref name=\"The Juilliard Journal\">{{cite web | url=http://www.juilliard.edu/journal/1411/discoveries/3-releases-jazz-grads | title=3 Releases From Jazz Grads | publisher=The Juilliard Journal | date=November 2014 | accessdate=6 October 2015 | author=Hodges, Bruce}}</ref> Batiste named the band [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]], which draws its moniker from the belief that human interaction during a live musical performance can uplift humanity in the midst of the \"plug in/tune out\" nature of modern society. The band leads impromptu street performances, which Batiste calls \"love riots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://joonbug.com/newyork/scenetracker/LoveRiot-A-Classic-Had-To-Be-There-NYC-Moment/pYKXZGHIHkh |title=#LoveRiot: A Classic \"Had To Be There\" NYC Moment |publisher=Joonbug.com |date=2012-04-11 |accessdate=2012-09-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Stay Human released the album ''MY N.Y.'', which was recorded in its entirety on [[New York City Subway]] trains, an idea that came to Batiste after questioning how to connect with people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/jonathan-batiste-and-the-stay-human-band-fill-the-subway-with-their-take-on-jazz-6433806|title=Jonathan Batiste and the Stay Human Band Fill the Subway with Their Take on Jazz|first=Larry|last=Blumenfeld|date=4 January 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2017, the band played for the [[March for Science]] rally at the Washington Monument in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2017/4/19/14331168/science-march-earth-day-route-livestream-signs-speakers|title=The March for Science on Earth Day, explained|last=Resnick|first=Brian|date=April 22, 2017|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2128541-on-the-ground-in-washington-at-the-march-for-science/|title=On the ground in Washington at the March for Science|last=Whyte|first=Chelsea|date=April 22, 2017|work=[[New Scientist]]|access-date=February 6, 2019|last2=Grossman|first2=Lisa}}</ref>\n\nThe band played their last full performance on the Colbert program before a scheduled weeklong vacation on March 12th, 2020, but then subsequently benched indefinitely following the lockdown ordered because of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. Colbert returned the week after with at home versions of the show joined only by Batiste on piano.\n\n==Television and film==\n{{BLP sources|section|date=January 2020}}\nIn 2014, Batiste and Stay Human appeared on ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' to perform the group's single \"Express Yourself\", written and produced with [[Austin Bis]]. On June 4, 2015, it was announced that the group would serve as house band on the ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]''. The show premiered on CBS on September 8, 2015. On the show, Batiste and Stay Human have performed alongside [[Billy Joel]], [[Will Smith]], [[Wynton Marsalis]], [[John Legend]], [[Grace VanderWaal]], and [[Nas]].\n\nBatiste was cast in the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Treme (TV series)|Treme]]'', appearing in seasons 2, 3 and 4. He was also cast as T.K. Hazelton in director Spike Lee's film ''[[Red Hook Summer]]'' and composed and performed the Hammond B-3 organ music that was a part of the film score. Other film scores composed by Batiste include the television documentary ''Duke 91 & 92: Back to Back'' and the short film ''Melody of Choice''. He also appears in the film ''[[Thrive (film)|Thrive]]'' by Paul Szynol.\n\n==Honors==\nBatiste was included in the 2016 ''Forbes'' 30 Under 30 music list<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web |title=Jon Batiste, 29 |url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/56704e09e4b0ffa7afe82b7c/jon-batiste-29/#2b6dc7e9728f |website=Forbes |accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> and was named Grand Marshal of Endymion Parade in New Orleans in 2018. He has been awarded the American Jazz Museum Lifetime Achievement Award, the Harry Chapin ASCAP Humanitarian Award and the [[Movado]] Future Legend Award. In May 2017, Batiste received an honorary degree from [[Salve Regina University]] for his musical achievements and contributions to Newport's 2014 International Jazz Day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://whatsupnewp.com/jon-batiste-to-present-2017-commencement-address-at-salve-regina-university/|title=George Wein, Jon Batiste to Receive Honorary Degrees from Salve Regina; Batiste to Give Commencement Address |date=2017-04-12|work=What'sUpNewp|access-date=2017-05-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBatiste lives in Brooklyn, New York, with his partner [[Suleika Jaouad]].<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/23/nyregion/jon-batiste-sunday-routine.html</ref> [[Teetotalism|He does not drink alcohol]].<ref>https://theundefeated.com/features/backstage-at-the-late-show-with-jon-batiste/</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with year released and chart positions \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"|Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Billboard 200|US]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Heatseekers Albums|US<br/>Heat]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Top Holiday Albums|US<br/>Holiday]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Independent Albums|US<br/>Indie]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Jazz Albums|US<br/>Jazz]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Times in New Orleans'' \n|2005\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Live in New York: At the Rubin Museum of Art'' \n|2006\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''In the Night'' \n|2008\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''The Amazing Jon Batiste!'' \n|2009\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''MY N.Y.'' EP (with [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]])\n|2011\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Social Music'' (with [[Stay Human (band)|Stay Human]])\n|2013\n|align=center|134<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jon-batiste/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Jon Batiste Chart History (Billboard 200)|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]])|accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=center|2<br/><ref name =\"HeatseekersHistory\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jon-batiste/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=Jon Batiste Chart History (Heatseekers Albums)|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|1<br/><ref name = \"JazzHistory\">{{cite web|url