eb.archive.org/web/20100906133130/http://home.online.no/~smogols/ifcp/clubs/ballymenaunited/clubballymenaunited.htm Ballymena United Statistics and Results at the Irish Football Club Project]\n{{Football in Northern Ireland}}\n{{NIFL league}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Ballymena United F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:NIFL Premiership clubs]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs in County Antrim]]\n[[Category:Sport in Ballymena]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Phoenix clubs (association football)]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:c82:df00:3051:d425:e141:61bd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ballymena_United_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Argentine Mauser Model 1909", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Mauser Modelo Argentino 1909\n| image= File:Argentinean Mauser (3808895358).jpg\n| image_size = 350\n|caption=\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Bolt-action]] [[rifle]]\n|service= 1905-1960s\n|used_by= Argentina<br>Paraguay\n|manufacturer= DWM<br>Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles\n|wars=[[Chaco War]]\n|is_ranged=yes\n|design_date=1909\n|production_date=1909-1959\n|number= ~285,000\n|weight={{convert|4.17|kg|lbs}}\n|length={{convert|124|cm|in}}\n|part_length={{convert|74|cm|in}}\n|cartridge=[[7.65\u00d753mm Mauser]]\n|action=[[Bolt-action]]\n|velocity={{convert|839.6|m/s}}\n|range=\n|feed=5-round [[stripper clip]], internal [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]]\n|sights= [[Iron sight]]s adjustable to {{convert|2000|m|yd}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Argentine Mauser Model 1909''' were [[Gewehr 98]] pattern bolt-action [[battle rifles]] designed for the [[Argentine Army]]. They were produced both in [[Germany]] and in [[Argentina]].\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Mauser1909 accion.jpg|thumb|left|The action of the Argentine Mauser 1909]]\nThe Mauser 1909 was a slightly modified copy of the Gewehr 98. Among other modifications, the ''Lange Vizier'' sight was replaced by a tangent leaf sight. The M1909 was also able to use the bayonet of the [[Mauser 1891]] it replaced.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}} The main producer in Germany was [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken]] that delivered 200,000 rifles{{sfn|Webster|2003|p={{page needed|date=July 2019}}}} while around 85,000 rifles{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}} were manufactured by the ''Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles'', governmental plants in [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]] and [[Santa Fe, Argentina|Santa Fe]]. The Model 1909s were replaced by [[FN FAL]]s{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=9}} without having seen combat{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=14}}.\n\nSome Argentine Mauser 1909 rifles and carbines without crests were sold to [[Paraguay]] during the [[Chaco War]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}}\n\n=== Variants ===\n* ''Mauser 1909 sniper rifle'': version with a German-made scope and a bent-down bolt handle.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=14}}\n* ''Mauser 1909 cavalry carbine'': shortened variant, with a straight grip stock and a forecap that covers all the barrel.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=15}} The bayonet can be attached under this forecap.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=18}}\n* ''Mauser 1909 Mountain Carbine'' or ''Engineers Carbine'': probably cut-down rifles{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=18}}\n\n== Peruvian Mauser 1909 ==\n[[File:US Navy 100705-N-5319A-229 Members of the Peruvian Marine Drill Team perform at the opening ceremonies of Amphibious-Southern Partnership Station 2010 at Ancon Marine Base, Peru.jpg|thumb|left|Peruvian ceremonial unit in 2010 with Mauser rifles.]]\n[[Peru]] received between 1910 and 1914 thousands of Mauser Model 1909 rifles, chambered in 7.65 Mauser. They were closer copies of the Gewehr 98, including the ''Lange Vizier'' sight.{{sfn|Ball|2011|pp=289-290}} Aside from the caliber, the only differences were the larger receiver ring, the {{convert|5|mm|abbr=on}} shorter breech, the slightly modified strip guide to use older Model 1891 strips, the longer [[Hammer (firearms)|hammer]], the aspheric shape of the bolt handle and the Peruvian markings.{{sfn|Guillou|2006|pp=23-24}} While these rifles were able to fire the old bullets with round nose, they were later adapted to [[Spitzer (bullet)|spitzer bullets]].{{sfn|Guillou|2006|pp=24-25}} These weapons were used during the [[Leticia Incident]] and the [[Ecuadorian\u2013Peruvian War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Latin American Wars 1900\u20131941: \"Banana Wars,\" Border Wars & Revolutions|series=Men-at-Arms 519|publisher=Osprey Publishing|first= Philip |last=Jowett|date= 28 Jun 2018|isbn=9781472826282 |pages=29, 46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8LJeDwAAQBAJ}}</ref> After 1945, the Mauser 1909s were replaced by American weapons and were sold in the civilian market in the 1960s, a few being kept as ceremonial rifles.{{sfn|Guillou|2006|p=25}}\n{{clr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ball|first=Robert W. D.|title=Mauser Military Rifles of the World|year=2011|location=Iola|publisher=Gun Digest Books|isbn=9781440228926|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Le fusil Mauser peruvien mod\u00e8le 1909 |language=fr|first=Luc|last=Guillou|magazine=[[Gazette des Armes]]|url=http://fr.1001mags.com/parution/gazette-des-armes/numero-382-decembre-2006/page-22-23-texte-integral|pages=22-25|ref=harv|date=December 2006|issue=382}}\n* {{cite book|title=Argentine Mauser Rifles 1871-1959|first=Colin |last=Webster|isbn=978-0764318689|year=2003|publisher=Schiffer Publishing|ref=harv}}\n{{Mauser Firearms}}\n\n[[Category:Rifles of Argentina]]\n[[Category:7.65\u00d753mm Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons of Peru]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Mauser Modelo Argentino 1909\n| image= File:Argentinean Mauser (3808895358).jpg\n| image_size = 350\n|caption=\n|origin=Germany\n|type=[[Bolt-action]] [[rifle]]\n|service= 1905-1960s\n|used_by= Argentina<br>Paraguay\n|manufacturer= DWM<br>Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles\n|wars=[[Chaco War]]\n|is_ranged=yes\n|design_date=1909\n|production_date=1909-1959\n|number= ~285,000\n|weight={{convert|4.17|kg|lbs}}\n|length={{convert|124|cm|in}}\n|part_length={{convert|74|cm|in}}\n|cartridge=[[7.65\u00d753mm Mauser]]\n|action=[[Bolt-action]]\n|velocity={{convert|839.6|m/s}}\n|range=\n|feed=5-round [[stripper clip]], internal [[Magazine (firearm)|magazine]]\n|sights= [[Iron sight]]s adjustable to {{convert|2000|m|yd}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Argentine Mauser Model 1909''' were [[Gewehr 98]] pattern bolt-action [[battle rifles]] designed for the [[Argentine Army]]. They were produced both in [[Germany]] and in [[Argentina]].\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Mauser1909 accion.jpg|thumb|left|The action of the Argentine Mauser 1909]]\nThe Mauser 1909 was a slightly modified copy of the Gewehr 98. Among other modifications, the ''Lange Vizier'' sight was replaced by a tangent leaf sight. The M1909 was also able to use the bayonet of the [[Mauser 1891]] it replaced.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}} The main producer in Germany was [[Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken]] that delivered 200,000 rifles{{sfn|Webster|2003|p={{page needed|date=July 2019}}}} while around 85,000 rifles{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}} were manufactured by the ''Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles'', governmental plants in [[Rosario, Santa Fe|Rosario]] and [[Santa Fe, Argentina|Santa Fe]]. The Model 1909s were replaced by [[FN FAL]]s{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=9}} without having seen combat{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=14}}.\n\nSome Argentine Mauser 1909 rifles and carbines without crests were sold to [[Paraguay]] during the [[Chaco War]].{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=12}}\n\n=== Variants ===\n* ''Mauser 1909 sniper rifle'': version with a German-made scope and a bent-down bolt handle.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=14}}\n* ''Mauser 1909 cavalry carbine'': shortened variant, with a straight grip stock and a forecap that covers all the barrel.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=15}} The bayonet can be attached under this forecap.{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=18}}\n* ''Mauser 1909 Moutain Carbine'' or ''Engineers Carbine'': probably cut-down rifles{{sfn|Ball|2011|p=18}}\n\n== Peruvian Mauser 1909 ==\n[[File:US Navy 100705-N-5319A-229 Members of the Peruvian Marine Drill Team perform at the opening ceremonies of Amphibious-Southern Partnership Station 2010 at Ancon Marine Base, Peru.jpg|thumb|left|Peruvian ceremonial unit in 2010 with Mauser rifles.]]\n[[Peru]] received between 1910 and 1914 thousands of Mauser Model 1909 rifles, chambered in 7.65 Mauser. They were closer copies of the Gewehr 98, including the ''Lange Vizier'' sight.{{sfn|Ball|2011|pp=289-290}} Aside from the caliber, the only differences were the larger receiver ring, the {{convert|5|mm|abbr=on}} shorter breech, the slightly modified strip guide to use older Model 1891 strips, the longer [[Hammer (firearms)|hammer]], the aspheric shape of the bolt handle and the Peruvian markings.{{sfn|Guillou|2006|pp=23-24}} While these rifles were able to fire the old bullets with round nose, they were later adapted to [[Spitzer (bullet)|spitzer bullets]].{{sfn|Guillou|2006|pp=24-25}} These weapons were used during the [[Leticia Incident]] and the [[Ecuadorian\u2013Peruvian War]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Latin American Wars 1900\u20131941: \"Banana Wars,\" Border Wars & Revolutions|series=Men-at-Arms 519|publisher=Osprey Publishing|first= Philip |last=Jowett|date= 28 Jun 2018|isbn=9781472826282 |pages=29, 46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8LJeDwAAQBAJ}}</ref> After 1945, the Mauser 1909s were replaced by American weapons and were sold in the civilian market in the 1960s, a few being kept as ceremonial rifles.{{sfn|Guillou|2006|p=25}}\n{{clr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ball|first=Robert W. D.|title=Mauser Military Rifles of the World|year=2011|location=Iola|publisher=Gun Digest Books|isbn=9781440228926|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Le fusil Mauser peruvien mod\u00e8le 1909 |language=fr|first=Luc|last=Guillou|magazine=[[Gazette des Armes]]|url=http://fr.1001mags.com/parution/gazette-des-armes/numero-382-decembre-2006/page-22-23-texte-integral|pages=22-25|ref=harv|date=December 2006|issue=382}}\n* {{cite book|title=Argentine Mauser Rifles 1871-1959|first=Colin |last=Webster|isbn=978-0764318689|year=2003|publisher=Schiffer Publishing|ref=harv}}\n{{Mauser Firearms}}\n\n[[Category:Rifles of Argentina]]\n[[Category:7.65\u00d753mm Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Mauser rifles]]\n[[Category:Sniper rifles]]\n[[Category:Weapons of Peru]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVariants:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_Mauser_Model_1909"}
